senses.sense: (obsolete) The science of remedies, or of therapeutics.
(prosody) A metrical foot in verse consisting of an unstressed syllable followed by a stressed syllable.
(prosody) A verse consisting of an iambic dimeter and half an elegiac pentameter.
plural of iambus
(prosody) Consisting of iambs (metrical feet with an unstressed-stressed pattern) or characterized by their predominance. 1
(prosody) An iamb; a line or group of lines of iambs.
Obsolete form of iambic.
According to iambic meter.
plural of iambic
One who writes in iambic meter.
(transitive) To satirize in iambics; to lampoon.
A poet who writes iambic verse.
plural of iamb
(prosody) iamb
plural of iambus
Any of the family Janthinidae of violet snails.
violet-coloured
(mineral) An orthorhombic-pyramidal mineral containing hydrogen, oxygen, and uranium.
(medicine) Pertaining to the application of remedies by rubbing, especially by rubbing in oil or balm.
(medicine) therapeutic inunction
Of or pertaining to a physician or physicians.
Alternative form of iatric
iatrochemical
Of or relating to iatrochemistry.
Someone who practiced iatrochemistry.
(chemistry, medicine) An early branch of chemistry, having roots in alchemy, that tried to provide chemical remedies to diseases; alternatively, the application of chemistry to medical theory.
(medicine, of a disease, injury, or other adverse outcome) Induced by the words or actions of the physician or by medical treatment or diagnostic procedure.
In an iatrogenic manner.
The quality of being iatrogenic.
Relating to iatrology.
Medical science.
(obsolete) Pertaining to a practice of medicine in conjunction with astrology.
(now rare) Pertaining to a theory or practice of medicine founded on mathematical principles.
Someone who studies iatromathematics; a physician applying a mathematical theory of medicine.
A 17th-century Italian doctrine that tried to apply the laws of mechanics and mathematics to the human body.
(historical, medicine) Describing a school of thought that maintained that physiology and pathology could be explained in terms of physics
(historical) A proponent of the iatromechanical theory.
(medicine) Of or relating to a 17th-century school of medical thought that explained all physiological and pathological phenomena by the laws of physics; opposed to the iatrochemical school.
(historical, medicine) A physician who was a follower of iatrophysics.
(obsolete) The physics of medicine or of medical and surgical treatment.
(obsolete) The treatment of diseases by physical or mechanic means.
Synonym of iatrotechnique
